The study, conducted by the Allameh Tabatabai University Center for Family Research in Iran, is published in the journal Contraception.

A total of 2,601 men aged 18 to 59 completed computer-assisted self interviews that were developed from previous questionnaires about perceptions about sex and contraception and beliefs about abortion.

About 71 percent of respondents believed that an abortion was an acceptable alternative to birth. Less than one-third (31 percent) viewed forced pregnancy as acceptable. In addition, about one-quarter (27 percent) of women believed they had the right to terminate the pregnancy, while 11 percent believed it was permissible to lie about the state of the pregnancy or to forcibly abort a pregnant woman.

"The findings revealed that the vast majority of the sample men see abortion as an acceptable alternative to birth, implying support of men regarding obtaining an abortion as concomitant with the near-unanimity of women regarding obtaining an abortion," the researchers wrote in their paper.

"While unwilling to beat a spouse or girlfriend to force her to have an abortion, men, in general, did not express refusal or disapproval of obtaining an abortion by other means."
